farmers who grow corn and most other feed 
grains in 1989 will have to idle only 10 percent of their base 
acreage to qualify for price supports and other government benefits 
this year farmers had to set aside 20 percent under the acreage 
reduction program or arp to qualify for benefits but drought cut 
yields sharply and siphoned off much of the nations grain 
stockpile thus restrictions were eased on next years plantings 
signup dates will be announced later agriculture secretary 
richard e lyng said friday 
besides corn the 10 percent arp will apply to 1989 crops of 
sorghum and barley oats will have a 5 percent idling requirement 
the same as in 1988 
lyng also announced some other provisions of the 1989 feed grain 
program including 
target prices for 1989 corn will be 284 per bushel down from 
293 this year sorghum 270 per bushel down from 278 
barley 243 per bushel down from 251 and oats 150 per 
bushel down from 155 
price support loan rates for corn will be 165 per bushel 
down from 177 this year sorghum 157 per bushel down from 
168 barley 134 per bushel down from 144 oats 85 cents 
per bushel down from 90 cents and rye which has no arp or target 
price 140 per bushel down from 150 
no marketing loan program will be implemented for feed grains 
in 1989 unchanged from 1988 
