<TEXT>
discoverys launch may start a new 
era for nasa but the astronauts still face one problem thats 
always bothered space travelers an uncomfortable comfort station 
during the 32 months the shuttle was grounded after challenger 
nasa made more than 200 changes aboard the craft but improving the 
space potty was not one of them astronauts still must contend with 
an orbiting john that has been known to turn a simple call of 
nature into a complex maneuver 
when the shuttle toilet was first installed it was said to be 
the final solution to a problem that has bothered astronauts since 
space travel began 
early astronauts learned that responding to a simple human need 
in space required a lot more effort than back home on earth there 
is gravity and something deposited somewhere tends to stay there 
but in space there is no gravity and anything not tied down or 
contained tends to float around 
during the gemini and apollo programs engineers designed 
systems that used flowing air to collect liquid wastes for solid 
wastes there were blue plastic bags that sealed after use 
astronauts hated the bags some resisted using the bags so strongly 
that they required medical attention upon return to earth 
for the shuttle engineers designed a space toilet filled with 
machinery and valves that promised the final solution for both 
genders the problem was to be solved with whirling blades 
freezedrying and collection by vacuum 
it was an almost immediate failure 
the system was so complicated that it required some fundamental 
toilet training on the ground and once in space astronauts found 
that equipment designed to remain pristine and fresh often became 
clogged and cranky after some missions the shuttle returned to 
earth smelling like an overused portable toilet 
the system was modified time after time but the complaints 
continued 
searching for answers johnson space center officials held 
closed door meetings with each returning astronaut hoping that the 
intrepid space fliers would recount personal anecdotes that would 
solve the problem but the terrors of the space toilet continued 
now an engineer at aerospace contractor hamilton standard co in 
windsor locks conn has proposed a system that officials hope 
will silence complaints 
don w rethke nicknamed dr flush by his coworkers 
designed a toilet that he says is simple sanitary and odorfree 
rethke said he originally designed the system for the space 
station the proposed orbiting laboratory where astronauts will 
live for months 
the hamilton standard design uses collection bags that are 
mounted in a device that resembles the commode back home the bags 
are automatically sealed compressed and stored in canisters and 
its simple astronauts merely push a button and wait for the 
machine to cycle they then insert a new bag for the next user and 
go on their way 
rethke said the space station system will collect and purify 
liquid waste and even recycle it for hygienic use 
nasa officials were so impressed with the concept they asked dr 
flush to submit a proposed design for the space shuttle other 
aerospace contractors also may submit designs but it was rethkes 
ideas that got the plan started 
they nasa engineers are tired of trying to solve the old 
problem he said this is a very simple system that may be the 
solution 
americas astronaut corps hopes so 
