<TEXT>
a house vote is expected next week on 
legislation that would impose the firstever restrictions on 
lobbying by exmembers of congress and former presidents and vice 
presidents 
the house judiciary committee by voice vote friday cleared the 
measure for floor action late next week in addition to its new 
restrictions the bill would expand existing lobbying prohibitions 
on former executive branch employees 
senior vice president ann mcbride of the selfstyled citizens 
lobby common cause called the committee vote a major step 
forward in the battle to enact this important ethics legislation 
the senate already has approved its own set of lobbying 
restrictions for those who quit the executive branch or leave 
congress both measures are aimed at those who leave the government 
and then immediately lobby their former colleagues usually on 
issues with which they were involved 
the american civil liberties union has sounded a cautionary 
note writing lawmakers that wholesale reform of the ethics laws 
is neither necessary nor desirable that is so because lobbying 
activity is political speech that is at the core of the first 
amendment 
indeed during committee debate several panel members who voted 
for the legislation argued the new restrictions could violate the 
constitutional right to free speech and they said there was no 
evidence of wrongdoing by exlawmakersturnedlobbyists 
congress wrote the current set of antilobbying laws in the 
postwatergate 1978 ethics in government act lawmakers did not 
include themselves in the restrictions because they believed all 
the abuses were in the executive branch 
the judiciary committee added an amendment this week to include 
former presidents and vice presidents in the restrictions but it 
defeated a proposal to restrict former federal judges from 
appearing before their excolleagues for a year after leaving the 
bench 
under the house bill members of congress would be banned for a 
year from representing someone before any current member officer 
or employee of the house where they served the restriction would 
not apply to speeches or personal advice 
members former personal office staffers and excommittee 
staffers would be prohibited from contacting their exbosses and 
colleagues for the yearlong period 
the bill also would prevent former executive branch officers 
from even aiding and advising someone on particular matters 
they worked on in government the language is aimed at 
behindthescenes strategists who might direct lobbying efforts 
without actually making government contacts themselves 
in cases where the former officials had a policy or program 
under their official responsibility the bill also would 
prevent them from aiding or advising for two years after 
leaving government 
the former executive branch officials already are banned from 
representing clients directly before the government for that 
period 
the measure also would impose a oneyear ban on representing 
aiding and advising someone on a trade matter which was under the 
exemployees official responsibility or in which he participated 
personally in the last year of government service 
there also would be changes in restrictions and coverage for 
senior executive branch personnel who generally would face a 
oneyear coolingoff period before lobbying former colleagues and 
agencies 
the house bill also would add civil penalties for violating the 
lobbying law thus giving the justice department a new option 
against violators in cases where criminal penalties would not be 
pursued 
