the reagan administration has defied a 
congressional mandate by failing to make available surplus federal 
property to the homeless a federal judge has ruled 
on friday us district judge oliver gasch said the 
administrations interpretation of the 1987 mckinney act 
arbitrarily restricts the scope of the statute 
gasch said the law named after the late rep stewart b 
mckinney rconn who died a few months after it was enacted in 
1987 is designed to make surplus federal property available to 
assist the homeless 
agreeing with the national coalition for the homeless he said 
only 12 facilities have been identified as underused by federal 
agencies and only two have been made available to the homeless 
