said the decision will require the agency to review federal surveys 
of surplus buildings to determine which are suitable for housing 
hud general counsel j michael dorsey said he did not know how 
many properties would be involved he said the order however does 
not apply to singleunit dwellings taken over by hud or the 
veterans administration because of defaults on governmentbacked 
housing loans 
sales of hud houses will continue said dorsey who described the 
decision as generally positive because it could help identify 
additional buildings that might be used for the homeless 
the order directs us to do more in more detail than we thought 
we had done in substantial compliance with the law he said 
the decision said its unreasonable to suggest that congress 
chose to lease to the homeless halfempty properties and properties 
which are used part of the time but not properties which are 
wholly unoccupied 
gasch said the court is persuaded that the defendants are not 
properly implementing the law pitifully few of the numerous 
unused federal properties are being evaluated for their suitability 
to assist the homeless those that are found to be suitable are not 
being made available to homeless providers 
ms maria foscarinis who represented the homeless coalition 
called the ruling a terrific decision 
the judge clearly and strongly holds that the administration 
has been violating the law in not making available underused 
federal property to the homeless she said 
ms foscarinis said in a telephone interview from new york that 
the significance of the ruling is that tens of thousands of 
properties across the country can now be used to save lives 
she said the buildings now standing vacant or partially used 
include barracks on military bases veteran administration 
hospitals and post office buildings 
nine days ago gasch refused to bar the department of housing 
and urban development from selling singlefamily homes it had 
acquired through mortgage foreclosures to the highest bidder 
he issued an order denying a preliminary injunction requested by 
a coalition of advocates for the homeless who had sought to block 
hud from selling 47000 foreclosed houses in its inventory 
