<TEXT>
federal officials called off a nationwide 
alert saturday after the nuclear reactor from a soviet military spy 
satellite ejected into high orbit obviating the danger of 
radioactive debris raining to earth 
the emergency is over said peg maloy spokeswoman for the 
federal emergency management agency which had coordinated 
extensive preparations to deal with any danger that might be posed 
by the satellite kosmos 1900 
she said pieces of the satellite had begun disintegrating in the 
earths atmosphere but added its just an ordinary drop 
theres no nuclear radiation involved 
right now everyone is breathing a real sigh of relief ms 
maloy said 
maj alex mondragon a spokesman at the us space commands 
space surveillance center in cheyenne mountain colo said the 
center is now tracking multiple objects in orbit apparently 
associated with a change in status in kosmos 1900 
there is debris in low orbit previously associated with kosmos 
1900 and now there is also new debris in a much higher orbit the 
additional debris is being catalogued and monitored by the us 
space command but preliminary analysis indicates that the object 
in higher orbit would remain there for many years he said 
mondragon said that the larger previously untracked object is 
currently assessed to be the reactor section with associated 
debris he said the reactor was orbiting the earth every 993 
minutes at an altitude of about 433 miles to 476 miles 
one piece of kosmos 1900 he said came down saturday morning 
over the atlantic ocean off the northwest coast of africa while 
another piece was orbiting at an altitude of about 91 miles its 
a small enough piece that we expect it to burn up he said 
in moscow the soviet news agency tass confirmed that kosmos 
1900 had shut down its reactor and separated with it when an 
automatic safety system began functioning 
the remaining part of the satellite instrument compartment 
which will shortly burn up in the dense layers of the atmosphere 
poses no radiation danger tass said 
earlier civil defense officials working with 15 other federal 
departments and agencies had made preparations to open an 
emergency center at the department of health and human services in 
washington and to help coordinate state and local efforts 
the soviet communist party newspaper pravda has called kosmos 
1900 a research satellite to observe the surface of oceans but 
us experts say it is part of the rorsat series the soviets use to 
track us warships 
rorsat carries a radarimaging device that beams radar waves to 
earth then analyzes the return signal to spot objects as small as 
destroyers the nuclear reactor provides the enormous power needed 
for the radar 
the satellite was designed to automatically fire rocket engines 
twice a week to correct a degrading orbit western experts noticed 
in april that the rockets were not firing and after reports 
appeared in the us and british media the soviets acknowledged 
that they had lost radio contact with kosmos 1900 
the soviets issued contradictory statements within the past week 
on when they lost radio contact with the satellite the soviet 
atomic energy committee statement said that in april 1988 radio 
communication with this satellite was interrupted 
but the communist party newspaper pravda ran an article by prof 
v serbin on thursday saying that radio communications with it 
stopped last june 
two earlier rorsat satellites have fallen from orbit the first 
was kosmos 954 which spewed radioactive flakes over 20000 square 
miles of northwestern canada on jan 24 1978 
the soviets redesigned the satellite and most subsequent 
rorsats ejected their nuclear reactors into a graveyard orbit 
600 miles above the earth while the satellites themselves largely 
burned up on reentry said oberg 
that system failed on kosmos 1402 which splashed into the 
indian ocean on feb 7 1983 however a backup system apparently 
ejected the nuclear reactor from the main body of the satellite and 
it disintegrated into dust on reentry according to american 
scientists 
robert leifer of the us energy departments environmental 
measurements laboratory wrote in the october 1987 edition of 
science magazine that the reactor disintegrated in the stratosphere 
47 miles over the indian ocean 
samples collected by a high altitude balloon accounted for 97 
pounds of the 110 pounds of uranium and related isotopes that 
rorsat is thought to have carried wrote leifer 
that means that radioactive dust settled slowly out of the 
atmosphere in concentrations too thin to endanger human life he 
said 
after kosmos 1900 falls the soviets will have no rorsats in 
orbit a condition that prevails about half the time said oberg 
the united states has considered launching satellites with 
nuclear reactors aboard but has never done so and it not believed 
to have a radarimaging satellite in orbit 
