<TEXT>
two experiments performed saturday 
aboard discovery ended a long wait for a couple of students whose 
projects originally were destroyed in the challenger explosion more 
than 2 years ago 
for lloyd c bruce who watched while his metalmelting 
experiment finally was performed in zero gravity the wait was well 
worth it 
it was great i had a lot of fun ive been working quite a 
while on it but im patient he said 
bruce a senior at the university of missouricolumbia was at 
the johnson space center on saturday and conducted his experiment 
along with discovery astronaut john m lounge 
richard s cavoils experiment was performed later by astronaut 
george d pinky nelson cavoli was not at jsc because he 
couldnt take time out from his medical school studies at the state 
university of new york at buffalo 
both 24yearolds were high school students bruce at sumner 
high school in st louis and cavoli at central high school in 
marlboro ny when their experiments were among those chosen as 
possible student projects for future shuttle missions both 
projects were assigned to the challenger mission which exploded 
jan 28 1986 
after the tragedy president reagan promised cavoli during his 
1986 state of the union address that his experiment would fly on a 
later shuttle mission 
cavolis experiment involved growing lead iodide crytals the 
experiment consisted of clear tubes that contained two chambers 
separated by a membrane 
lead acetate was in one end and a solution of potassium iodide 
was in the other chamber the solutions were allowed to meet at the 
membrane where they formed crystals 
bruces experiment consisted of a small furnace to test the 
effects of weightlessness on melted titanium a metal used in 
airplanes and atomic power plants he also conducted the experiment 
on earth so differences between the two can be later studied 
at the same time bruce and lounge flipped power switches that 
heated one wire at a time a closeup television view from discovery 
showed the titanium wires glowing brightly after they were heated 
after the experiments were completed bruce said the one done in 
space seemed to have performed as expected with two of the wires 
melting and then breaking 
and bruce said he hopes it isnt the end of his participation in 
the space program 
i hope to be an astronaut bruce said adding he plans to 
apply for nasas mission specialist program after he earns a 
masters degree this is one of my dreams 
yes saturday was fun but he added its not like being 
there i want to be there 
</TEXT>
