<TEXT>
muriel snowden cofounder of the nonprofit 
freedom house that pushed for integration and selfhelp in bostons 
predominantly black roxbury section has died at the age of 72 
mrs snowden who died at home friday night of cancer won a 
prestigious macarthur foundation grant last year 
she and her husband otto began freedom house in 1949 after 
calling 17 people to their home to confer about how black and white 
residents could unite on common problems 
they ran the organization from their home for three years then 
bought a building that had been a church and a teachers college 
when the snowdens retired in 1984 they had made freedom house a 
catalyst for urban renewal job fairs affirmative action and 
innovative school programs they were also a force for calm during 
the school integration crisis of the 1970s 
the work of an organization like ours is never done mrs 
snowden once said 
in june 1987 she was one of 32 people awarded no strings 
grants by the john d and catherine t mararthur foundation 
fellows receive annual stipends for a fiveyear period ranging 
from 30000 to 75000 a year 
in june the boston school committee voted to rename a high 
school in her honor 
mrs snowden is survived by her husband a daughter and a 
granddaughter 
funeral arrangements were incomplete 
