<TEXT>
the senate approved friday and sent president 
reagan a 466 billion agriculture money bill that limits a 
threeyearold export subsidy that has spurred overseas sales of 
us grain 
the bill approved 904 by the senate in the final congressional 
vote contains 466 billion in budget authority for a wide array 
of programs ranging from farm payments to food stamps 
the budget authority level was down from 562 billion last year 
while outlays under the bill would total only 269 billion 
farm appropriations often reflect a wide gap between budget 
authority and actual outlays for one thing the 88 billion 
earmarked for the governments commodity credit corp is really a 
reimbursement for a revolving fund and not counted as an outlay 
the commodity credit corp operates the agriculture departments 
major crop subsidy programs 
other bigticket items included in the measure 136 billion 
for food stamps 1929 billion for the nutrition program for 
women infants and children 148 billion for humanitarian food 
exports and 1864 billion for the conservation reserve program 
the conservation reserve program pays farmers to take highly 
erodible acreage out of crop production for a decade 
the measure provides for 770 billion under the export 
enhancement program the program makes inkind payments of surplus 
crops to exporters to send american wheat feed grains and other 
commodities overseas 
a substantial increase in sales is attributed to the program 
which was established under wideranging 1985 farm legislation in 
return the government has paid more than 2 billion worth of 
commodities to the worlds largest grain companies and other 
exporters 
the house in quest of budget savings had sought to cap the 
program at 900 million for the fiscal year getting under way 
saturday but housesenate conferees ended up adopting the senate 
level 
the bill also held to 200 million spending under the 1985 
targeted export assistance program it pays for advertising and 
other promotion of american agricultural products in overseas 
markets 
it had been authorized at 325 million in the upcoming fiscal 
year but appropriations committee lawmakers slashed out 125 
million after the program came under criticism within the house for 
using taxpayer funds to advertise specific brands of agricultural 
products 
the measure also attempts to close a loophole under which the 
nations commercial honey producers have been circumventing a limit 
of 250000 a year for any individual on gains through forfeiture 
of pricesupport loans 
under normal farm programs farmers use their crops for 
collateral to obtain the loans and then deliberately forfeit if 
that would yield them greater earnings than selling on the open 
market the commodity credit corp in effect becomes the buyer 
and supports a price set by the government rather than by the 
market 
lawmakers thought they had capped the benefits at 250000 
several years ago but the nations commercial beekeepers were able 
to find a perfectly legal route around the restriction 
the senate also sent the money bill to the president amid 
complaints about the job status of george dunlop the assistant 
secretary of agriculture for natural resources and environment 
dunlop got into a political rumpus with powerful house 
appropriations chairman jamie whitten dmiss and the panel 
erased dunlops job from the bill the senate refused to go along 
and the fate of the former aide to sen jesse helms rnc became 
a painful point between the two chambers 
meanwhile capitol hill wags produced lapel buttons that said 
save george dunlop 
the house was in effect trying to do away with his job and 
in effect to do away with him sen thad cochran rmiss said 
he said however that house and senate conferees had agreed on two 
other job titles that dunlop could get with the approval of 
agriculture secretary richard lyng 
