by the london library of which he was president 
critics recalled the antisemitic expressions in some of eliots 
poetry and letters 
in the 1927 poem burbank with a baedeker bleistein with a 
cigar eliot wrote the rats are underneath the piles the jew 
is underneath the lot 
the poet also said in a lecture in january 1933 as adolf hitler 
was about to take power in germany reasons of race or religion 
combine to make any large number of freethinking jews undesirable 
and a spirit of excessive tolerance is to be deprecated 
 
some critics say eliot in time put aside antisemitism and that 
it had no role in his later life 
eliot is much in favor these days because his ideas are now 
fashionable said poet harry gilonis he was a classicist a 
monarchist an anglocatholic and very conservative while in his 
poetry he was a modernist attacked in his day for pessimism and 
formlessness 
eliot wasnt appreciated by the public then but he is admired 
now and with paperbacks for a mass market more and more people 
are reading his work 
</TEXT>
