<TEXT>
michael caine in period costume of long sideburns 
and tweed coat settles into a victorian chair in the quiet drawing 
room of the 18thcentury mansion 
its an appropriately chilly rainy london day but the next 
room is blazing bright under the quite 20thcentury lights of the 
movie company filming cbs jack the ripper 
the twopart miniseries airing friday and sunday oct 21 and 
23 marks the centennial of the grisly unsolved serial killings 
writerdirector david wickes used scotland yard files that had been 
sealed for a century to develop a theory of the killers identity 
that will be revealed at the end of the film 
the miniseries is caines first television role in more than 20 
years his first on american tv 
the last time he did television at all caine recalls he 
costarred with christopher plummer in a british production of 
hamlet 
of course i didnt play hamlet in that this time i do he 
says with mock smugness 
he plays the central character in the drama scotland yard 
inspector frederick abberline the miniseries costars armand 
assante and jane seymour 
caine said he was completely disinterested in returning to tv 
until the miniseries genre came along 
over a period of time the miniseries had become a very valid 
way of filming things that wouldnt fit into an hour and 50 minutes 
or two hours and 10 in the movies he said and so therefore 
it gained a lot of prestige as far as i was concerned where you 
could do good stuff rather than just television slop 
i wouldnt have done it if it had been done with five tv 
cameras and everybody rushing around trying to change velcro suits 
because i did all that thats what i remembered television as 
because i did about a hundred shows different plays live on 
television and all i remember is a very inefficient nightmare and 
if you remembered all the dialogue you were a genius never mind if 
you got the performance that didnt make any difference 
then this script came along which i liked particularly and 
it was a kind of definitive jack the ripper because we do catch 
the guy theres been a lot of jack the ripper movies but theres 
never been an ending now weve got the real ending 
jack the ripper was the nickname for the unknown killer who 
stalked and eviscerated five east london prostitutes the killings 
came to an abrupt end on nov 9 1888 the identity of the ripper 
according to wickes theory will be revealed when the 
americanbritish coproduction airs in england oct 18 until then 
even caine wont know the ending because wickes filmed four 
different ones 
abberline diligently investigated the ripper case but never made 
an arrest wickes maintains he was thwarted by a coverup that 
extended to the highest offices of the land 
caine found abberline to be a very tenacious bulldog copper 
kind of rough he wasnt adverse to smacking someone around in the 
cells or anything like that to get what he wanted if he figured 
they were villains 
caine had recently finished playing another detective a comical 
version of sherlock holmes in the movie without a clue due out 
this month ben kingsley plays watson who in this premise has 
invented sherlock holmes as a front when forced to produce him he 
hires a neerdowell actor caine to play the part 
working on without a clue and jack the ripper in england 
allowed caine to help his family adjust to their recent move back 
to his homeland after nine years in los angeles caine 55 was 
born maurice micklewhite in a cockney district of london he 
decided to leave los angeles after wearying of the monotonous 
weather that prevented him from fully indulging his passion for 
gardening 
later caine was off to the south of france to costar with 
steve martin in dirty rotten scoundrels which he described as 
a comedy about two not very efficient con men trying to live off 
old ladies 
in 1987 he starred in two british spy thrillers the fourth 
protocol for which he was executive producer and the whistle 
blower he also starred in the critically acclaimed 1983 british 
film educating rita and had a supporting role in mona lisa 
in 1986 but much of caines success had been in american movies 
among them too late the hero the man who would be king 
sleuth and jaws iv the revenge 
his supporting role in woody allens 1986 best picture hannah 
and her sisters won him his first oscar after three previous 
nominations caine said he would like to work with allen again but 
has no idea if the reclusive director liked him enough to write him 
into another film even after winning an academy award for the 
picture 
that doesnt matter to him at all he doesnt believe in 
them caine said adding over his shoulder as he headed back to 
the set probably because i won the oscar he wont give me 
another part 
