<TEXT>
the latest batch of government figures suggest the economy is 
growing modestly and will avoid recession through 1989 but 
investors were more concerned with falling oil prices 
the commerce department said friday its chief forecasting gauge 
of future economic activity rose a moderate 04 percent in august 
indicating to analysts that growth will continue through next year 
but at a slower pace 
the gain in the index of leading economic indicators follows a 
06 percent drop in july and a 15 percent jump in june the index 
is intended to predict economic activity six to nine months in 
advance 
in another report the commerce department said new 
singlefamily homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 
713000 units in august up 01 percent from july and unchanged 
from june 
it was the best threemonth performance since februaryapril 
1987 when longterm mortgage rates dipped below 9 percent and 
spurred a housing sales boom 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the reports were 
good news for the economy and suggest continued economic 
growth 
but those reports were largely bypassed in the financial 
markets where strategists were trading on news that oil prices had 
skidded to nearly 13 a barrel in panicky trading the lowest level 
in more than two years 
the oil decline was caused partly by speculation that saudi 
arabia the worlds largest exporter might flood the world with 
crude and wrench prices down drastically 
reverberations from the oil selloff spilled into the currency 
market where the dollar fell sharply on trader fears that 
declining energy prices would ease inflation pressure and thereby 
depress interest rates in the united states gold also fell on the 
prospect of lower inflation 
in the bond market a sensitive barometer of inflation and 
interest rates prices rose sharply and yields on the key 30year 
treasury issue fell to 898 percent from 906 percent 
but investors in the stock market reacted indecisively to the 
oil decline reflecting a wariness that has pervaded wall street in 
the nearly one year since the oct 19 1987 crash 
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks up about 18 
points at its midsession high closed with a 640 loss at 211291 
the broader market was mixed 
</TEXT>
