<TEXT>
panic trading sparked by renewed fears of an 
oversupply of world oil sent crude prices to the lowest level in 
more than two years and some analysts say prices will continue 
weakening 
on the new york mercantile exchange friday the contract for 
november delivery of west texas intermediate the benchmark us 
crude closed down 55 cents at 1337 a 42gallon barrel after 
dropping to a session low of 1325 
it was the lowest closing level since aug 4 1986 when the 
nearterm contract settled at 1329 a barrel 
analysts said indications that saudi arabia is flooding the 
market with oil in an effort to discipline other members of the 
organization of petroleum exporting countries renewed investor 
anxieties about weakening oil prices 
predictions from opec secretarygeneral subroto that prices 
could hit 5 a barrel created panic selling analysts said 
subrotos statements followed a report by an industry 
publication that the opec is producing about 3 million barrels a 
day over their implied ceiling of 175 million barrels 
many analysts predicted that prices will weaken further in the 
near future 
prices will continue to decline said james steel an 
analyst with refco inc but they should hold around 12 a 
barrel 
in other trading activity friday wholesale unleaded gasoline 
prices rose to settle at 4789 cents a gallon compared with 
thursdays closing price of 4642 cents a gallon other contract 
months declined 
analysts said the gains in gasoline stemmed partly from the 
recent hurricane threat in the gulf of mexico when refineries and 
oil rigs halted operations 
production statistics released this week showed that although 
gasoline inventories were up 22 million barrels on a weekly basis 
to 219 million barrels they were 10 million barrels below the same 
period a year earlier 
heating oil fell 150 cents to end the day at 3804 cents 
